06960nam a22007815i 9781554589210DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545892107 a10.51644/97815545892102doi  a(DE-B1597)667429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1998.3 G63L44 2014 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4302/3309222304aThe Legacies of Jean-Luc Godard /ced. by Christina Stojanova, Douglas Morrey, Nicole Côté. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (274 p.) :b23 b&w and colour illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Media Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tGodardian Legacy in Film, Music, and Dance -- tJean-Luc Godard, Christophe Honoré, and the Legacy of the New Wave in French Cinema -- tJean-Luc Godard: Dans le noir du temps (2002)— The “Filming” of a Musical Form -- tJean-Luc Godard and Contemporary Dance: The Judson Dance Theater Runs Across Breathless -- tGodardian Politics of Representation: Memory/ History -- tThe Representation of Factory Work in the Films of Jean-Luc Godard -- tGodard, Spielberg, the Muselmann, and the Concentration Camps -- t“The Obligations of Memory”: Godard’s Underworld Journeys -- tJean-Luc Godard’s Histoire(s) du cinéma Brings the Dead Back to the Screen -- tGodardian Legacy in Philosophy -- tJean-Luc Godard and Ludwig Wittgenstein in New Contexts -- tGodard, Schizoanalysis, and the Immaculate Conception of the Frame -- tThe “Hidden Fire” of Inwardness: Cavell, Godard, and Modernism -- tThe Romance of the Intellectual in Godard: A Love–Hate Relationship -- tFormalist Legacies: Narratives and Exhibitions -- tPrinciples of Parametric Construction in Jean-Luc Godard’s Passion -- t“A Place of Active Judgment”: Parametric Narration in the Work of Jean-Luc Godard and Ian Wallace -- tGodard’s Utopia(s) or the Performance of Failure -- tFilmography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the Film+Media Studies Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe artistic impact of Jean-Luc Godard, whose career in cinema has spanned over fifty years and yielded a hundred or more discrete works in different media cannot be overestimated, not only on French and other world cinemas, but on fields as diverse as television, video art, gallery installation, philosophy, music, literature, and dance. The Legacies of Jean-Luc Godard marks an initial attempt to map the range and diversity of Godard’s impact across these different fields. It contains reassessments of key films like Vivre sa vie and Passion as well as considerations of Godard’s influence over directors like Christophe Honoré. Contributors look at Godard’s relation to philosophy and influence over film philosophy through reference to Wittgenstein, Deleuze, and Cavell, and show how Godard’s work in cinema interacts with other arts, such as painting, music, and dance. They suggest that Godard’s late work makes important contributions to debates in memory and Holocaust Studies. The volume will appeal to a non-specialist audience with its discussions of canonical films and treatment of themes popular within film studies programs such as cinema and ethics. But it will also attract academic specialists on Godard with its chapters on recent works, including Dans le noir du temps (2002) and Voyage(s) en utopie (2006), interventions in long-running academic debates (Godard, the Holocaust, and anti- Semitism), and treatment of rarely discussed areas of Godard’s work (choreographed movement).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film